categories.title: Roles in development and planning
categories.description: These personnel model, design, procure and/or build secure IT systems and are responsible for the development of systems and networks.

categories.title: Operational and administration roles
categories.description: These personnel provide the support, administration and maintenance necessary to ensure the efficient and effective operation and security of IT systems.

categories.title: Supervisory, leadership, educational and support roles
categories.description: These personnel are in leadership roles, in a managerial position, setting the direction and direction of development or representing the organisation to enable it to operate in the cybersecurity field.

categories.title: Roles in protection against cyber security threats within the CERT team
categories.description: These personnel identify, analyse and eliminate threats to internal IT systems and/or networks.

categories.title: Analytical roles
categories.description: These personnel perform highly specialized research and evaluation of cybersecurity information and determine its usefulness.

categories.title: Roles in collection operations
categories.description: These personnel conduct specialized access prevention or deception operations and collect cybersecurity information of value.

categories.title: Investigation roles
categories.description: These personnel investigate cybersecurity incidents or crimes related to IT systems, networks, and work with electronic evidence.

competencies.title: Asset and Inventory Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the process of identifying, developing, operating, maintaining, upgrading, and disposing of assets.

competencies.title: Business Continuity
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to business continuity planning and continuity of operations to help ensure an organization can prevent and overcome serious incidents or disasters and quickly resume normal operations within a reasonable timeframe.

competencies.title: Strategic Relationship Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the concepts, practices, and techniques used to identify, engage, influence, and monitor relationships with individuals and groups connected to a work effort—including those actively involved, those who exert influence over the process and its results, and those who have a vested interest in the outcome (positive or negative)—to build strategic relationships and achieve common goals.

competencies.title: Collection Operations
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to executing the collection of cybersecurity information to develop intelligence using appropriate strategies and within the priorities established through the collection management process.

competencies.title: Digital Forensics
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the application of tools and techniques used in data recovery and preservation of electronic evidence. Includes the collection, processing, preservation, analysis, and presentation of computer-related evidence in support of law enforcement agencies or intelligence services.

competencies.title: Computer Languages
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to computer languages and their applications in order to enable a system to perform specific functions.

competencies.title: Computer Network Protection
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities that relate to the protective measures aimed to detect, respond, and protect information, information systems, and networks from external and internal threats.

competencies.title: End-point Device Security
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to building, maintaining, repairing, and securing electronic devices, associated peripherals, and accessories.

competencies.title: Conflict Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to managing and resolving conflicts, grievances, confrontations, or disagreements in a constructive manner to minimize negative personal impact and collaborating with others to encourage cooperation and teaming.

competencies.title: Contracting and Procurement
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to procuring, negotiating, administering, and managing various types of contracts, including application of contracting or procurement techniques and requirements according to applicable laws and policies.

competencies.title: Law, Policy, and Ethics
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to awareness of and compliance with laws, regulations, policies, and ethics that can impact organizational activities.

competencies.title: Critical Thinking
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to analysis, reasoning, problem solving, planning, and organization to make inferences or draw conclusions that enable sound decision-making.

competencies.title: Data Analysis
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to systematically applying statistical and logical techniques to describe, illustrate, condense, summarize, and evaluate data. The synthesis and analysis of various types of data to reach a decision, make a recommendation, or to compile reports, briefings, executive summaries, and other correspondence to support organizational work, goals, and plans.

competencies.title: Data Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the development and execution of data management plans, programs, practices, processes, architectures, and tools across all stages of the data lifecycle. Includes processes around the creation, storage, archiving, discovery, access, disposal, as well as enhancement, and reuse of data and information assets.

competencies.title: Data Privacy
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the proper handling of data to protect individuals´ privacy, including addressing whether and how data is shared and with whom; how data is collected and stored; and legal and regulatory compliance.

competencies.title: Database Administration
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to principles, methods, and tools for managing and maintaining database systems used to store and organize data to maximize the value, quality, and usability of data resources. May include the development and enforcement of database standards, guidelines, and operational policies and procedures.

competencies.title: Encryption
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the cryptographic process of transforming data to ensure their integrity and confidentiality.

competencies.title: Enterprise Architecture
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, concepts, and methods of enterprise architecture to align technology strategy, plans, and systems with the mission, goals, structure, and processes of the organization.

competencies.title: Awareness of Broader Context
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities that relate to identifying and understanding how internal and external economic, political, social trends impact the activities of the organization.

competencies.title: Identity Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the tools, policies, and systems that define, manage, and monitor the roles and secure access privileges of users, ensuring authorized people and devices have the appropriate access to the correct protected resources at the correct time.

competencies.title: Incident Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the tactics, technologies, principles, and processes to analyze, prioritize, and handle cybersecurity incidents.

competencies.title: Data Security
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the methods and procedures that protect data and information systems by ensuring their confidentialty, integrity, and availability.

competencies.title: Information Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities that relate to where or how to gather, organize, maintain, or modify information or information management systems to effectively process, store, and/or distribute information.

competencies.title: Information Systems and Network Security
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the methods, tools, and procedures—including development of information security plans—to detect, respond, and protect information, information systems, and networks from risks and to provide or restore security of information systems and network services.

competencies.title: Information Technology Assessment
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools (for example, surveys, system performance measures) to assess the effectiveness and practicality of technology systems.

competencies.title: Infrastructure Design
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the architecture and topology of software, hardware, and networks, including LAN, WAN, and telecommunications systems, their components and associated protocols and standards, and how they operate and integrate with one another and with associated controlling software.

competencies.title: Intelligence Analysis
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the application of individual and collective cognitive methods to collect, process, and interpret data about a target to answer tactical questions about current operations or to predict future behavior.

competencies.title: Interpersonal Skills
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to developing and maintaining relationships with others in order to work effectively. Includes being sensitive to and inclusive of cultural diversity, race, gender, disabilities, and other individual differences as well as considering and responding appropriately to the needs, feelings, and capabilities of customers and colleagues (subordinates, peers, and superiors).

competencies.title: Knowledge Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the management and administration of processes and tools that enable the organization to identify, document, and access intellectual capital and information content.

competencies.title: Mathematical Reasoning
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to solving practical problems and determining if an assertion is correct by choosing appropriately from a variety of mathematical and statistical techniques.

competencies.title: Modeling and Simulation
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to mathematical modeling and simulation tools and techniques to plan and conduct test and evaluation programs, characterize systems support decisions involving requirements, evaluate design alternatives, or support operational preparation.

competencies.title: Network  Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the operation, management, and maintenance of computer network and telecommunication systems and linked systems and peripherals.

competencies.title: Operating Systems
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to computer operating systems.

competencies.title: Operations Support
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the policies and procedures used to ensure the production or delivery of products and services, including tools and mechanisms for distributing new or enhanced hardware and software.

competencies.title: Communication
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the process of clearly and effectively expressing information or ideas to individuals or groups in a variety of ways (verbal, nonverbal, written, and visual). Includes understanding when and how to adapt messages for different audiences as well as listening to others’ instructions, ideas and intentions, attending nonverbal cues, and responding appropriately.

competencies.title: Organizational Awareness
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to understanding an organization’s mission and functions; its structure; and how programs, policies and regulations impact the objectives of the organization.

competencies.title: Policy Development
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the process of creating, communicating, and maintaining organizational principles and policies within an organization.

competencies.title: Problem Solving
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to determining the accuracy and relevance of information; using sound judgment to generate and evaluate alternatives; and making well-informed, objective recommendations and decisions that take into account facts, goals, constraints, and risks while perceiving the impact and implications of the decisions.

competencies.title: Process Control
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related monitoring of processes and their adjustment based on the results.

competencies.title: Project Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools for developing, scheduling, coordinating, and managing projects and resources, including monitoring and inspecting costs, work, and contractor performance.

competencies.title: Requirements Analysis
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles and methods to identify, analyze, specify, design, and manage functional and infrastructure requirements—includes translating functional requirements into technical requirements used for logical design or presenting alternative technologies or approaches.

competencies.title: Risk Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools used for risk assessment and mitigation, including assessment of failures and their consequences. Includes the oversight, evaluation, and support of the documentation, validation, assessment, and authorization processes necessary to assure that existing and new technology systems meet organizational cybersecurity and risk requirements.

competencies.title: Software Development
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools for designing, developing, modifying and testing software in a given environment, embodying all the stages throughout the software development lifecycle.

competencies.title: Software Testing and Evaluation
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools for developing, administering, and analyzing software testing to evaluate, verify, and validate technical, functional, and performance characteristics (including interoperability).

competencies.title: Strategic Planning
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to formulating effective tactics and metrics associated with the vision, mission, goals, and objectives of the organization.

competencies.title: System Administration
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the installation, configuration, troubleshooting, and maintenance of computer systems to ensure their confidentiality, integrity, and availability. Includes the management of accounts, firewalls, and patches as well as access control, passwords, and account creation and administration.

competencies.title: Systems Integration
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and procedures for installing, integrating, and optimizing information systems components.

competencies.title: Systems Testing and Evaluation
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools for developing, administering, and analyzing systems test procedures to evaluate, verify, and validate technical, functional, and performance characteristics (including interoperability) of systems or elements of systems incorporating technology. Includes the identification of critical operational issues.

competencies.title: Target Development
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the systematic examination of potential target systems - and their components, individual targets, and even elements of targets - to determine the necessary type and duration of the action that must be exerted on each target to create an effect that is consistent with the organizations objectives.

competencies.title: Education and Training Delivery
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to helping others acquire knowledge or develop skills.  Includes training of personnel within pertinent subject domain, including cybersecurity awareness for users of computers, mobile phones and other devices.

competencies.title: New Technology Fluency
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to keeping up to date on technological developments, including new applications of technology, emerging technologies, and the effective use of technology to achieve results.

competencies.title: Telecommunications
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the transmissions, broadcasting, switching, control, and operation of telecommunications and related network infrastructure.

competencies.title: Threat Analysis
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the identification and assessment of adversaries’ or foreign intelligence entities’ cybersecurity attack capabilities and activities. Includes awareness and evaluation of internal and external information vulnerabilities that may be at risk to cyber-attacks.

competencies.title: Supply Chain Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the process of analyzing and controlling risks presented through the products or services purchased from third parties.

competencies.title: Vulnerabilities Assessment
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to the principles, methods, and tools for assessing vulnerabilities and developing or recommending appropriate mitigation countermeasures.

competencies.title: Web Technology Fluency
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities that relate to the principles and methods of web technologies, tools, and delivery systems, including web security, privacy policy practices, and user interface issues as they apply to web development.

competencies.title: Workforce Management
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to building and managing a productive workforce based on organizational goals, budget considerations, and staffing needs. It related to ensuring that employees are appropriately recruited, selected, appraised,and rewarded. Part of it is ability to take action to address performance problems. It further includes retention and career pathing strategies (including mentoring or coaching) for a variety of work situations.

competencies.title: Business Acumen
competencies.description: This Competency describes understanding of key business issues and the strategic management of human, financial, and information resources in order to achieve desired organizational outcomes. Includes taking into account internal and external influences (e.g., business, economic, political, social trends) in decision making.

competencies.title: Education and Training Curriculum Development
competencies.description: This Competency describes capabilities related to developing, planning, coordination, delivery, and evaluation of training courses, methods, and techniques.

competencyGroups.title: Technical
competencyGroups.description: Competencies proving adequate training and technical knowledge for cybersecurity activities.

competencyGroups.title: Organizational
competencyGroups.description: Organisational competencies relevant to communication, coordination and leadership of cybersecurity activities.

competencyGroups.title: Professional
competencyGroups.description: Competencies through which the specific professional knowledge and competence is demonstrated.

competencyGroups.title: Leadership
competencyGroups.description: Competencies that are a prerequisite for leading teams, coordinating activities or managing the running of an organisation or part of an organisation.

requirements.description: Ability to identify systemic security issues based on the analysis of vulnerability and configuration data.
Ability to match the appropriate knowledge repository technology for a given application or environment.
Ability to determine the validity of technology trend data.
Ability to develop curriculum that speaks to the topic at the appropriate level for the target audience.
Ability to decrypt digital data collections.
Ability to prepare and deliver education and awareness briefings to ensure that systems, network, and data users are aware of and adhere to systems security policies and procedures.
Ability to tailor code analysis for application-specific concerns.

Ability to apply the methods, standards, and approaches for describing, analyzing, and documenting an enterprise IT architecture (e.g. National Cyber and Information Security Agency, The European Union Agency for Cybersecurity).
Ability to apply supply chain risk management standards (eg. ISO 28000).
Ability to analyze malware.
Ability to answer questions in a clear and concise manner.
Ability to ask clarifying questions.
Ability to communicate complex information, concepts, or ideas in a confident and well-organized manner through verbal, written, and/or visual means.
Ability to communicate effectively when writing.
Ability to conduct vulnerability scans and recognize vulnerabilities in security systems.
Ability to facilitate small group discussions.
Ability to gauge learner understanding and knowledge level.
Ability to prepare and present briefings.
Ability to produce technical documentation.
Ability to provide effective feedback to students for improving learning.
Ability to use and understand complex mathematical concepts (e.g., discrete math).
Ability to apply principles of adult learning.
Ability to design valid and reliable assessments.
Ability to develop clear directions and instructional materials.
Ability to accurately define incidents, problems, and events in the trouble ticketing system.
Ability to analyze test data.
Ability to apply an organization's goals and objectives to develop and maintain architecture.
Ability to assess and forecast manpower requirements to meet organizational objectives.
Ability to build complex data structures and use high-level programming languages (C, C++, Java, Python, etc.).
Ability to collect, verify, and validate test data.
Ability to conduct and interpret market research to understand available capabilities and appropriate pricing.
Ability to develop curriculum for use within a virtual environment.
Ability to develop policy, plans, and strategy in compliance with laws, regulations, policies, and standards in support of organizational cyber activities.
Ability to develop, update, and/or maintain standard operating procedures (SOPs).
Ability to dissect a problem and examine the interrelationships between data that may appear unrelated.
Ability to identify basic common coding flaws.
Ability to leverage best practices and lessons learned of external organizations and academic institutions dealing with cyber issues.
Ability to optimize systems to meet enterprise performance requirements.
Ability to oversee the development and update of the full cost estimate.
Ability to translate data and test results into evaluative conclusions.
Ability to use data visualization tools (e.g., Flare, HighCharts, AmCharts, D3.js, Processing, Google Visualization API, Tableau, Raphael.js).
Ability to develop career path opportunities.
Ability to conduct forensic analyses in and for both Windows and Unix/Linux environments.
Ability to apply programming language structures (e.g., source code review) and logic.
Ability to evaluate/ensure the trustworthiness of the supplier and/or product.

Ability to monitor and assess the potential impact of emerging technologies on laws, regulations, and/or policies with regards to the information offered by relevant authorities and research entities.
Ability to develop secure software according to secure software deployment methodologies, tools, and practices.
Ability to apply network security architecture concepts including topology, protocols, components, and principles (e.g., application of defense-in-depth).
Ability to apply secure system design tools, methods and techniques.
Ability to apply system design tools, methods, and techniques, including automated systems analysis and design tools.
Ability to execute technology integration processes.
Ability to operate network equipment including hubs, routers, switches, bridges, servers, transmission media, and related hardware.
Ability to determine trends in workforce data (availability, cost, conditions of employment etc.).
Ability to apply the Instructional System Design (ISD) methodology.
Ability to operate common network tools (e.g., ping, traceroute, nslookup).
Ability to ensure security practices are followed throughout the acquisition process.
Ability to execute OS command line (e.g., ipconfig, netstat, dir, nbtstat).
Ability to operate the organization's LAN/WAN pathways.
Ability to build architectures and frameworks.
Ability to monitor measures or indicators of system performance and availability.
Ability to operate different electronic communication systems and methods (e.g., e-mail, VOIP, IM, web forums, Direct Video Broadcasts).
Ability to interpret and translate customer requirements into operational capabilities.
Ability to monitor traffic flows across the network.
Ability to accurately and completely source all data used in intelligence, assessment and/or planning products.
Ability to adjust to and operate in a diverse, unpredictable, challenging, and fast-paced work environment.
Ability to apply approved planning development and staffing processes.
Ability to apply collaborative skills and strategies.
Ability to apply critical reading/thinking skills.
Ability to apply language and cultural expertise to analysis.
Ability to clearly articulate intelligence requirements into well-formulated research questions, requests for information and data tracking variables.
Ability to collaborate effectively with others.
Ability to coordinate and collaborate with analysts regarding requirements for essential information development.
Ability to coordinate cyber operations with other organization functions or support activities.
Ability to coordinate, collaborate and disseminate information to other organizations.
Ability to effectively employ each organization or element into the collection plan and matrix.
Ability to develop or recommend analytic approaches or solutions to problems and situations for which information is incomplete or for which no precedent exists.
Ability to develop or recommend planning solutions to problems and situations for which no precedent exists.
Ability to effectively collaborate via virtual teams.
Ability to evaluate information for reliability, validity, and relevance.
Ability to evaluate, analyze, and synthesize large quantities of data (which may be fragmented and contradictory) into high quality, fused intelligence products.
Ability to exercise judgment when policies are not well-defined.
Ability to expand network access by conducting target analysis and collection to identify targets of interest.
Ability to focus research efforts to meet the customer’s decision-making needs.

Ability to function in a collaborative environment, seeking continuous consultation with other analysts and experts—both internal and external to the organization—to leverage analytical and technical expertise.
Ability to identify external partners with common cyber operations interests.
Ability to identify intelligence gaps.
Ability to identify/describe target vulnerability.
Ability to identify/describe techniques/methods for conducting technical exploitation of the target.
Ability to interpret and apply laws, regulations, policies, and guidance relevant to organization cyber objectives.
Ability to interpret and understand complex and rapidly evolving concepts.
Ability to monitor system operations and react to events in response to triggers and/or observation of trends or unusual activity.
Ability to participate as a member of planning teams, coordination groups, and task forces as necessary.
Ability to include decryption capabilities/tools into network collection tactics, techniques, and procedures.
Ability to include decryption capabilities/tools for wireless collection procedures.
Ability to recognize and mitigate cognitive biases which may affect analysis.
Ability to recognize and mitigate deception in reporting and analysis.
Ability to review processed target language materials for accuracy and completeness.
Ability to select the appropriate implant to achieve operational goals.
Ability to tailor technical and planning information to a customer’s level of understanding.
Ability to think like threat actors.
Ability to understand objectives and effects.
Ability to utilize multiple intelligence sources across all intelligence disciplines (i.e., HUMINT, GEOINT, MASINT, OSINT, SIGINT, TECHINT, CYBINT/DNINT, FININT).
Ability to monitor advancements in data protection and cybersecurity laws to ensure organizational adaptation and compliance.

specializationAreas.title: Communication with the public
specializationAreas.description: Personnel communicate the organisation's cyber security position and actions to the wider public and speak on its behalf when engaging with the media.

specializationAreas.title: CERT Team management
specializationAreas.description: Personnel supervise, manage and lead the work of the CERT team.

specializationAreas.title: Technology research and development
specializationAreas.description: Personnel perform technology evaluation and integration processes. They provide and develop prototypes of new functionalities and evaluate their usability.

specializationAreas.title: Risk management
specializationAreas.description: Personnel oversee, evaluate, and support the documentation, validation, authorization, and assessment processes needed to ensure that existing or new IT systems meet the organization's security requirements. They ensure adequate risk reflection, compliance with regulatory requirements, and internal and external safeguards.

specializationAreas.title: Software and hardware development
specializationAreas.description: Personnel develop and program new (or modify existing) computer applications, software, hardware or specialized programmable tools in accordance with best practice safeguards for software and hardware development.

specializationAreas.title: Applied cryptography development
specializationAreas.description: Personnel develop tools leading to the protection of information and communication by means of mathematical codes in a method that is readable only on the basis of specific knowledge or technology.

specializationAreas.title: System architecture
specializationAreas.description: Personnel develop system concepts and work on system functionality within the development cycle. They translate technology and regulatory requirements into the system, its security design and processes.

specializationAreas.title: Testing and evaluation
specializationAreas.description: Personnel prepare and conduct testing and evaluation of systems for compliance with specifications and requirements. They apply cost-effective planning principles and methods. They evaluate, verify and validate technical, functional and performance characteristics, including interoperability between systems and their elements.

specializationAreas.title: System development
specializationAreas.description: Personnel work in the development phase of the system development cycle.

specializationAreas.title: Data management
specializationAreas.description: Personnel create and maintain databases and data management systems that enable the storage, analysis, protection and use of that data.

specializationAreas.title: Knowledge management
specializationAreas.description: Personnel manage and maintain the processes and tools that enable the organisation to identify, document and access know-how and collected knowledge.

specializationAreas.title: System requirements planning
specializationAreas.description: Personnel consult with customers to identify and evaluate their functional requirements and translate them into technical solutions. They provide support to customers on the usability of information systems for their business needs.

specializationAreas.title: Customer service and technical support
specializationAreas.description: Personnel resolve problems related to installation, configuration or error messages. They perform maintenance and training according to customer requirements. They usually provide initial information about a security incident to a team specialised in dealing with these situations.

specializationAreas.title: Network services
specializationAreas.description: Personnel install, configure, test, operate, maintain, and manage networks and their firewalls, including hardware (i.e., hubs, bridges, switches, routers, cables, proxies) and software components that enable the sharing and transmission of data across multiple spectrums, in support of the security of the systems and the data being processed.

specializationAreas.title: Systems administration
specializationAreas.description: Personnel install, configure, troubleshoot, and maintain server configurations (both hardware and software components) to ensure confidentiality, integrity, and availability. They manage accounts, firewalls and patches. They are responsible for access control, password management, account creation and account management.

specializationAreas.title: Vulnerability analysis
specializationAreas.description: Personnel gather information on identified vulnerabilities and the potential for exploitation.

specializationAreas.title: Security incident response
specializationAreas.description: Personnel monitor the network and systems, detect threats and security incidents, and respond to detected cybersecurity incidents on protected networks and systems in an effort to promptly prevent harm from occurring or expanding. Using remediation, protection, reactive and recovery tools, they seek to maximize functionality, protect assets and data. They investigate and analyze relevant response activities.

specializationAreas.title: Analysis of information from all sources
specializationAreas.description: Personnel analyze threat information from all available sources across the cybersecurity community. They synthesize and contextualize this information and draw relevant conclusions.

specializationAreas.title: System analysis
specializationAreas.description: Personnel examine the organization's current system equipment and processes and develop solutions that improve the safety, efficiency and effectiveness of its operations. In doing so, they combine knowledge of business processes with IT expertise and are therefore able to understand the limits and requirements of both.

specializationAreas.title: Legal counsel and representation
specializationAreas.description: Personnel provide legal support and recommendations to management and staff in relevant regulatory areas. They advocate for policy changes in response to regulation, represent the organisation and provide legal documentation.

specializationAreas.title: Training, education and awareness raising
specializationAreas.description: Personnel conduct training and exercises in relevant areas. They prepare, plan, coordinate, provide and evaluate training materials, methods and techniques as needed and provide public education and outreach.

specializationAreas.title: Target analysis
specializationAreas.description: Personnel apply their knowledge of a particular domain, country, entity, or technology.

specializationAreas.title: Language analysis
specializationAreas.description: Personnel apply their specific linguistic, cultural, and technical knowledge to support information acquisition, analysis, and implementation of cybersecurity activities in a given linguistic or cultural context.

specializationAreas.title: Information gathering operations
specializationAreas.description: Personnel collect data according to relevant information collection strategies and with respect to established priorities in managing information collection processes.

specializationAreas.title: Cybersecurity operations
specializationAreas.description: Personnel conduct detailed planning and execution of cybersecurity operations. They gather information and prepare detailed operational plans and instructions. They provide planning at strategic and operational levels across operations in a collaborative and coordinated manner. They conduct target tracking and other cybersecurity operations as assigned.

specializationAreas.title: Cybersecurity investigations
specializationAreas.description: Personnel apply approaches, techniques, and procedures using a variety of investigative tools including interviewing, interrogation, surveillance, counter-surveillance, and surveillance detection. They appropriately balance the benefits of prosecuting detected crimes with the opportunity for additional information-valued data collection.

specializationAreas.title: Cybersecurity management
specializationAreas.description: Personnel supervise, direct, and lead the organization's cybersecurity work. They address strategic direction, staffing, technical infrastructure, requirements, enforcement of security policy, crisis procedures, threat monitoring, and other aspects.

specializationAreas.title: Strategic planning and action
specializationAreas.description: Personnel develop plans and policies or propose and enforce policy changes to achieve the organization's goals and priorities, taking into account the requirements and parameters of the environment.

specializationAreas.title: Project management and acquisition planning
specializationAreas.description: Personnel apply knowledge of data structures, processes, relationships, analytical procedures, systems, networks, and information exchange assumptions to guide programs. They perform hardware, software and information systems acquisition and other management tasks.

specializationAreas.title: International cooperation
specializationAreas.description: Personnel speak on behalf of the organization within international collaboration structures to communicate its position, negotiate coordination of activities, and share information within relevant working groups.

specializationAreas.title: CERT Penetration testing
specializationAreas.description: Personnel apply procedures and tools for early detection of security flaws and vulnerabilities in information systems before they are exploited by an attacker.

specializationAreas.title: Digital forensics
specializationAreas.description: Personnel collect, process, secure, analyze, and present electronic evidence of network threats and vulnerabilities for use in cybercrime investigations, fraud detection, counterespionage, or criminal prosecution.

specializationAreas.title: CERT Analysis in the context of cyber security threat protection
specializationAreas.description: CERT personnel use cybersecurity tools and information gathered from available sources to identify, analyze, and report threats that have happened or may happen within a protected network or system.

specializationAreas.title: CERT Cybersecurity threat protection infrastructure support
specializationAreas.description: CERT personnel test, deploy, maintain, and manage the hardware and software infrastructure to protect against cybersecurity threats. They monitor the network and respond to unauthorized activity.

specializationAreas.title: CERT Security incident response
specializationAreas.description: CERT personnel respond to detected cybersecurity incidents on protected networks and systems in an effort to promptly prevent harm or threatened harm. Using remediation, protection, reactive and recovery tools, they seek to maximize functionality, protect assets and data. They investigate and analyze relevant response activities.

specializationAreas.title: CERT Vulnerability assessment and management
specializationAreas.description: CERT Personnel evaluate threats and vulnerabilities. They determine if and how systems and networks deviate from acceptable configurations, applicable requirements, or accepted security policy. They assess the level of risk and prepare or recommend appropriate countermeasures.

specializationAreas.title: Threat analysis
specializationAreas.description: Personnel identify and assess the capabilities and activities of cyber security attackers. The findings are the basis for action by competent authorities or for additional intelligence gathering and cybersecurity operations.

workRoles.title: Penetration testing specialist
workRoles.description: Uses tools and procedures (e.g. simulations of attacker behaviour) for early detection of security flaws and vulnerabilities in information systems before they are exploited by an attacker.

workRoles.title: CERT Cybersecurity analyst
workRoles.description: Uses data collected through various CERT cybersecurity tools (e.g. IDS alerts, firewall logs, network traffic logs) to analyse captured events for potential threats.

workRoles.title: CERT Support specialist for cybersecurity threat protection infrastructure
workRoles.description: Tests, deploys, maintains and manages hardware and software infrastructure to protect against cybersecurity threats.

workRoles.title: CERT Security incident response specialist
workRoles.description: Investigates, analyzes and responds to detected cybersecurity incidents on protected networks and systems.

workRoles.title: CERT Vulnerability manager
workRoles.description: Conducts assessments of systems and networks for potential cybersecurity vulnerabilities. Detects whether and how these systems and networks deviate from acceptable configurations, applicable requirements or accepted security policy. Measures the effectiveness of defense-in-depth architectures against known vulnerabilities.

workRoles.title: Threat analyst
workRoles.description: Prepares and operates status indicators for various processes and functions within a given operational environment. Collects, processes, analyzes, reports, and provides alerts on identified threats.

workRoles.title: Threat analyst for disruptive technologies
workRoles.description: Collects, processes, analyses, reports and provides alerts on actual or potential threats arising from the development and implementation of disruptive technologies, e.g. IoT, blockchain or quantum computing.

workRoles.title: Vulnerability analyst
workRoles.description: Works to identify gaps in target systems, and how they can be exploited. Uses all permissible sources and analytical techniques to penetrate the network of the selected target.

workRoles.title: Cybersecurity analyst
workRoles.description: Uses data collected through various cybersecurity tools (e.g., IDS alerts, firewall logs, network traffic logs) to analyze captured events for potential threats.

workRoles.title: Cryptanalyst
workRoles.description: Works to uncover opportunities to break cryptographic protection and tools in order to gain access to encrypted data.

workRoles.title: Information analyst
workRoles.description: Analyzes data from available sources, for reconnaissance and preparatory assessment of the environment, to determine required information and provide required intelligence collection as a basis for further planning and course of operations.

workRoles.title: Operations evaluation analyst
workRoles.description: Develops plans and methodologies to evaluate performance and effectiveness. Evaluates the strategic and operational effectiveness of cybersecurity missions. Evaluates whether the system is performing as required and provides input to determine operational effectiveness.

workRoles.title: Targets analyst
workRoles.description: Analyzes target systems, creating and updating records of relevant targets based on input from preparatory environmental analyses and available external or internal sources of information. Performs advanced analysis of collected data to maintain current knowledge of targets, define their activities, and develop procedures to obtain more information about the target. Determines how the target communicates, acts, and operates based on knowledge of their technology assets, online connections, and their use. Works with partners and intelligence organizations to determine appropriate targets for verification and validation.

workRoles.title: Analyst with language or cultural specialization
workRoles.description: Uses his/her specific linguistic or cultural knowledge relevant to the target or threat information and his/her technical expertise to extract such information from, for example, audio or graphic materials in the language. Creates and maintains databases reflecting linguistic and cultural specificities and tools to support cybersecurity operations affecting the environment. Uses his/her expertise in activities and projects with a given linguistic or cultural interdependence.

workRoles.title: Manager of information collection from available sources
workRoles.description: Identifies relevant sources and environments for information collection; considers information requirements in data collection management. Manages available information collection assets; formulates and modifies information collection plans. Oversees the proper conduct of a given information collection and adherence to the collection plan.

workRoles.title: Manager responsible for collection requirements from available sources
workRoles.description: Evaluates information collection operations and determines information collection requirements taking into account available resources and methods to optimize data collection.

workRoles.title: Expert conducting information collection
workRoles.description: Performs information collection and categorization for security or other specified purposes.

workRoles.title: Manager of cybersecurity intelligence activities
workRoles.description: Prepares detailed plans for gathering information to meet the requirements of a given cybersecurity operation. Works with the cybersecurity operations coordinator to determine, verify, and achieve collection and analysis requirements. Participates in target selection, validation, and execution of the operation. Synchronizes intelligence activities to align with organizational objectives.

workRoles.title: Cybersecurity intelligence expert
workRoles.description: Performs intelligence collection to meet the requirements of a given cybersecurity operation.

workRoles.title: Cybersecurity operations coordinator
workRoles.description: Prepares detailed plans for the conduct and execution of a given set of cybersecurity operations in coordination with other coordinators, specialists, and analysts. Participates in target selection, validation, and execution of a given operation.

workRoles.title: Partner integration coordinator
workRoles.description: Works to develop cooperation with partners in cybersecurity operations. Assists with engaging partner cybersecurity teams through support, resourcing, and collaboration to develop best practices and coordinate support from the organization to achieve the objectives of joint cybersecurity operations.

workRoles.title: Cybersecurity operations specialist
workRoles.description: Conducts tracking of relevant objectives. Navigates networks, performs tactical forensics, and executes cybersecurity operations as assigned.

workRoles.title: Cybercrime investigator
workRoles.description: Identifies, collects, examines, and secures electronic evidence using validated and documented analytical and investigative procedures.

workRoles.title: Cybercrime forensic analyst
workRoles.description: Conducts detailed examination of cybercrime, detects it, and creates documentation of electronic evidence findings, e.g., by examining recorded media or available security incident logs.

workRoles.title: Cybersecurity forensic analyst
workRoles.description: Analyzes electronic evidence and investigates security incidents to obtain useful information to eliminate system and network vulnerabilities.

workRoles.title: Malware analyst
workRoles.description: Analyzes suspected files obtained during incident resolution using static and dynamic analysis, reverse engineering, and other analysis of related documents or scripts.

workRoles.title: Expert in securing and handling of electronic evidence
workRoles.description: Applies knowledge relevant to securing electronic evidence, reflects specific procedures and uses appropriate tools for preservation and further disposition.
